<br>
His dear mother, a woman of intense love and security.  Maia reminded him of cotton candy.  Warm and sugary, and very very soft.  When his mother is around, Hermes just wanted to be enfolded in her arms, and fall into an endless sleep, filled with dreams of pink fluffy clouds.  Adrift in her love, Hermes knew that his mother contained the passion and ferocity of a raging lioness.  He knew for sure that no matter what he may do, no one was going to ever hurt him, not as long as she is around.  Staring into her starry eyes, he saw within, a dedication to motherhood so strong that it made his heart ache.  He knew that he only wanted to make her happy and proud.  Hermes wanted to kiss his mother, but knew that a sign of affection at this moment would not be appropriate.  So he settled for holding her hand instead.<br>
<br>
Hestia, his aunt, appeared to be a lady, that deserved utmost respect.  But Hermes mental powers were already fully developed, as is those of every god and goddess upon their birth.  Hermes realized that underneath his aunt's demeanor, is a goddess filled with warm and dedicated love of life.  She was like a rich Gaul eclair.  Crispy and fresh on the outside, but oozing with delicious laughter and love on the inside.  Hermes mentally noted that, if he ever got in trouble, especially with his mother, he knew his Aunt Hestia would be there for him.<br>
<br>
Then there is Ares, his half-brother.  It seems ranking and status is very important here on Olympus, and it seems Ares felt it was very important as well.  Even from a distance, Hermes could feel the aura of power and dedication his brother contained.  But of what is he so dedicated to?  In his mind, Hermes thought of Ares as strong, Greek wine.  Made with the spicyest grapes from the famous vineyards of Athens, and aged with hidden and secret spices.  Only the most brave dared to try, and only with the most cautionary of sips.  That was what Hermes thought his brother was like.  And true to Hermes nature for mischief, he wanted to try the wine over and over.  Maybe he'll be intoxicated, maybe he'll get burnt, but he knew that he was going to have a lot fin, and get into a lot of trouble with Ares.  And so Hermes smiled, a small sly twitch of his lips, as he watched Ares disappear.  He knew they were going to cross paths many many times.<br>
<br>
Even before his Aunt Aphrodite appeared, a fanfare of trumpets and the singing of lovebirds heralded her aunt's appearance.  It seemed as if she was floating, but all immortals could do that.  It seemed as if she was floating, not because of her own doing, but because of the bountiless praises and devotions offered to her from her countless worshippers.  She is Love incarnate.  Hermes liked her right from the start.  It wasn't because he was a male, it was because that was what she demanded.  It was impossible not to love Love.  She had a sinful taste to her.  Like the decadent chocolate made from cocoa beans in a land far far to the west.  Where only the royalty of that far away kingdom were allowed to sample that nectar.  Seeing her approach, and watching the reaction of the other males in the room, Hermes began scheming.  How could he get his aunt into trouble, without being caught.  It seemed as if she wanted to be naughty.  All her worshippers, their basest desire was to have Aphrodite ooze and seep into every pore of their body.  What a naughty idea!  Hermes would have blushed except he was too young to realize the conotations.  But then again, maybe not.<br>
<br>
And in came a being of extraordinary radiance.  Hermes had seen statues all over the Mediterranean, and none of them did justice to this being.  If perfection was real, then this must be him.  As Hermes looked, it seemed as if tiny bits of light were surrounding his brother.  Looking closer, he realized that they were tiny stars, orbiting around Apollo.  For even they knew that Apollo is the Lord of Light, Keeper of the Sun.  As Apollo approached, and offered a gift to Hermes.  Hermes liked his brother immediately.  His brother tasted like an ice cream cone eaten on a hot and bristling afternoon.  His brother's glory may be intense, but his love is like a cool salve that tempers the intense heat.  HoldingApollo's gift, Hermes realized that he wanted to offer something in return.  But he wanted to do it in a very special and symbolic way, Hermes style.  Then he remembered that there was a herd of Apollo's cattle not too far from where he and his mother lived.  A plan that involved cattle, stealing, and a lyre quickly hatched into his mind.  Grinning mischieviously at his brother, Hermes said his thanks.<br>
<br>
The sudden chill that filled the room only meant one thing.  His uncle Hades had arrived.  With utmost respect, Hermes turned around to meet his uncle.  Dressed in rich velvet embroidered with the many tales of Hades conquest, Hades was an entity not to be trifled with.  It seemed as if an invisible breeze meant only for Hades was blowing through his cape.  Then Hermes realized that it was the breathes of many souls, souls still left uncollected on the mortal realm.  Hermes understood the significance of this encounter.  He knew that not only was he to be the messenger of the Gods, but he would become the Bearer of Souls.  He knew that he would be intricately incolved with his uncle, as he guided recently departed souls into his uncle's nether realms.  His uncle tasted like ancient ginseng, recently unearthed and very potent.  A root of immense power and mystical abilities, hidden from the outside world, and only barely understood.  That was what Hades tasted like to Hermes.  Such ancient secrets were hidden within Hades, this Hermes was sure of.  After all, souls of countless eons resides in Hades realm.  And what secrets they held in mortal life, Hades now held in immortal afterlife.  Bowing with respect like he had been taught by his mother, Hermes replied in a strong but reverent voice, &quot;Hermes, sir.&quot;<br>
