<br>
Hermes wondered what kind of trouble will occur now that both husband and wife are together.  After all, Hades had managed to keep Persephone all to himself for half a year, and the fact that Persephone is here indicated that her time underground was over.  So spring must be here too.<br>
<br>
Casting a quick glance at Hades, he saw true love in those ebony eyes.  But Hades is a gentleman, true to his soul, and he wouldn't force Persephone back, unless it was by her own free will.<br>
<br>
Smiling at his young cousin, brimming with youthful energy.  Hermes happily accepted the treat his cousin had brought him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you&quot; Hermes said around a mouthful of cotton candy.<br>
<br>
As he licked his fingers, cleaning the lingering pieces of spun sugar off, he listened intently to the conversation Persephone was having with his mother.  <br>
<br>
He thought Persephone was a lot like the crystal fresh spring water found only in the hidden springs of the Himalayas.  The yogis of those hidden temple selfishly kept the treasure to themselves, for they knew how potent the liquid in clearing up the mind.  In fact, many of them often began their meditations with a drink of the water, as a rite of purification of the mind.  <br>
<br>
As Hermes listened, he became more and more more worried about meeting Hera and Zeus.  Were they really as bad as everyone made them out to be?  He knew that he had to make his own decisions, and he knew that his first encounter with them will surely set the stage of their relationships.<br>
<br>
Hermes held his mother's hand even tighter.<br>
